<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09102d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09102d">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09102d"> 102(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Rome 2 apostles</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The society of the faithful bore a just proportion to the capital of the empire; and the Roman church was the greatest, the most numerous, and, in regard to the West, the most ancient of all the Christian establishments, many of which had received their religion from the pious labors of her missionaries. Instead of one apostolic founder, the utmost boast of Antioch, of Ephesus, or of Corinth, the banks of the Tiber were supposed to have been honoured with the preaching and martyrdom of <mark>the two most eminent among the apostles</mark>; and the bishops of <mark>Rome</mark> very prudently claimed the inheritance of whatsoever prerogatives were attributed either to the person or to the office of St. Peter. <small> Edward Gibbon, <a name="EGDF2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGDF2"><cite title="source">Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire</cite></a> (ed. unknown) I, (Chapter XV) 475</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
